Detailed Description

A coordinate (COO) format sparse matrix. This uses the ``struct of arrays'' storage paradigm. An example of the opposite storage paradigm, ``array of structs,'' would be an array of coord_elem_t (which see).

Field Documentation

int* coo_matrix_t::II

For entry e, II[e] is its row (we can't call it I because that is reserved as a macro in C99 for sqrt{-1})

enum index_base_t coo_matrix_t::index_base

Base of indexing (either one or zero)

int* coo_matrix_t::JJ

For entry e, JJ[e] is its column

int coo_matrix_t::m

Number of rows

int coo_matrix_t::n

Number of columns

int coo_matrix_t::nnz

Number of stored (nonzero) entries. If the matrix is stored in a symmetric (or skew, etc.) format, nnz only refers to the number of stored entries, not the actual number of nonzeros.

enum symmetric_storage_location_t coo_matrix_t::symmetric_storage_location

If the matrix has a kind of symmetry (or skew-symmetry): Where the actual elements of the matrix are stored: in the lower triangle or the upper triangle.

enum symmetry_type_t coo_matrix_t::symmetry_type

Symmetry type of the matrix.

void* coo_matrix_t::val

For entry e, val[e] is its value. Type of the entries depends on the value of value_type.

enum value_type_t coo_matrix_t::value_type

Indicates the type of the entries in val: REAL means "double", COMPLEX means "double _Complex", PATTERN means the "val" array is NULL and contains no entries.
